{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508987"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:11:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:11:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11366"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11366"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.03,0.75,0.09,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4011"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111317"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4011"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11366"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93445"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"3012"},{"type":"tags","id":"3514"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"6364"},{"type":"tags","id":"11620"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4283"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4364"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4855"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11475"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11525"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11570"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33436"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43218"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45195"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46114"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111317"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman attends the General Practice clinic for antenatal review at 31 weeks gestation. She is G1P0 with a pregnancy complicated only by Gestational Diabetes, diagnosed at her oral glucose tolerance test (OGTT) at 28 weeks. Her OGTT results revealed a fasting blood glucose level (BGL) of 5.2 mmol/L (\u0026lt;5.3) and her 2 hour postprandial BGL is 11.2 mmol/L (\u0026lt;11.0). Her fasting glucose at 14 weeks gestation was 4.9 mmol/L and HbA1c was 6.2% (\u0026lt;6.5).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe was initially reviewed by a credentialed diabetes educator and commenced an appropriate diet and regular exercise. She has been monitoring her BGLs at home four times daily (fasting, and postprandially) using a glucometer. Over the last week she has had at least one 2 hour postprandial readings on a daily basis above 8 mmol/L (target \u22646.7 mmol/L) despite being conscientious with her diet and exercise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the patient appears well and vital signs are within the normal range. Her current BMI is 32 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Her BMI pre-pregnancy was 28 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in the management of this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Empagliflozin","Glipizide","Insulin","Semaglutide","Weight loss"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has gestational diabetes mellitus (GDM).\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003EScreening for women without underlying risk factors occurs at 24-28 weeks. GDM is diagnosed by using an oral glucose tolerance test or fasting glucose test with one or more of the following results:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFasting glucose\u00a0 \u22655.3 mmol/L\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1\u2010hr glucose\u00a0 \u00a0 \u2265\u00a010.6 mmol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2\u2010hr glucose\u00a0 \u00a0\u2265 9.0 mmol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECurrently, ADIPS\u00a0Consensus\u00a0Guidelines\u00a0for\u00a0the\u00a0Testing\u00a0and\u00a0Diagnosis\u00a0of\u00a0Gestational\u00a0Diabetes\u00a0Mellitus\u00a0in\u00a0Australia (2025) recommend identifying those with moderate or high risk factors for GDM, to enable earlier case detection. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHigh risk factors for GDM include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevious\u00a0GDM\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPreviously\u00a0elevated\u00a0blood\u00a0glucose\u00a0level\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMaternal\u00a0age\u00a0\u226540\u00a0years\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFamily\u00a0history\u00a0diabetes mellitus\u00a0(1st\u00a0degree\u00a0relative\u00a0with\u00a0diabetes\u00a0or\u00a0a\u00a0sister\u00a0with\u00a0GDM)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBMI\u00a0\u0026gt;\u00a035\u00a0kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevious\u00a0macrosomia\u00a0(baby\u00a0with\u00a0birth\u00a0weight\u00a0\u0026gt;\u00a04500\u00a0g\u00a0or\u00a0\u0026gt;\u00a090th\u00a0centile)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPolycystic\u00a0ovarian\u00a0syndrome\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMedications:\u00a0corticosteroids,\u00a0antipsychotics\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EModerate risk factors for GDM include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAncestry including Asian, Indian, First Nations Australians, Pacificer Islander, Maori, Middle Eastern or non-white African\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBMI\u00a025\u00a0\u2013\u00a035\u00a0kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor patients with risk factors present, such as high BMI in this patient, the 2025 Gestational Diabetes guidelines recommend a first trimester screening HbA1c test, which in this case was normal, resulting in routine recommendations for OGTT between 24-28 weeks.. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHuman placental lactogen plays a key role in the development of GDM by inducing insulin resistance. Elevated levels of glucose in the maternal blood can lead to both maternal (e.g. gestational hypertension, urinary tract infections, preeclampsia) and fetal (e.g. macrosomia, neonatal hypoglycaemia, polycythaemia) complications. It is imperative that maternal glucose levels be controlled within normal limits. The first-line management of antenatal hyperglycaemia is lifestyle modifications consisting of dietary changes and exercise with the aim for a stable maternal weight or weight loss in the morbidly obese population groups. If these interventions cannot maintain strict BGLs, then pharmacological intervention is indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe recommended BGL targets for people with GDM are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFasting blood glucose: \u0026lt;5.3 mmol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBGL 2-hours post-prandial: \u0026lt;6.7 mmol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe first line pharmacological treatment for Gestational Diabetes is \u003Cstrong\u003Einsulin\u003C/strong\u003E. Insulin does not cross the placenta. The only oral antihyperglycaemic drug that can be considered for hyperglycaemia in pregnancy is metformin, with no compelling evidence of adverse pregnancy outcomes nor teratogenic effects. However, metformin crosses the placenta, and recent meta-analyses demonstrate increased central adiposity and obesity in metformin-exposed children, thus, its use is controversial. Metformin is also contraindicated in the presence of known fetal growth restriction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther oral hypoglycaemic medications (e.g. \u003Cstrong\u003Eglipizide, empagliflozin\u003C/strong\u003E), as well as GLP-1 agonists (e.g. \u003Cstrong\u003Esemaglutide\u003C/strong\u003E) are not recommended in pregnancy, due to concerns for potential teratogenicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eweight loss \u003C/strong\u003E(or maintaining a stable weight) may be beneficial for this patient outside of pregnancy, actively trying to lose weight in the second and third trimesters is generally not advisable. Instead, women with GDM should focus on managing their weight through a healthy diet and exercise, under the guidance of their healthcare provider.\u00a0Additionally, weight loss alone is unlikely to be sufficient to induce and maintain euglycaemia, given lifestyle interventions thus far have been ineffective.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The first-line pharmacological treatment (after lifestyle modifications) for gestational diabetes is insulin"],"references":["Sweeting A, Hare MJ, de Jersey SJ, Shub AL, Zinga J, Foged C, Hall RM, Wong T, Simmons D. Australasian Diabetes in Pregnancy Society (ADIPS) 2025 consensus recommendations for the screening, diagnosis and classification of gestational diabetes. Med J Aust. 2025 Aug 4;223(3):161-167. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40544364/","Hyperglycaemia in pregnancy (including gestational diabetes) [published 2019 Jan]. In: eTG complete [digital]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2021 Mar. Available at: https://www.tg.org.au","Rowan JA, Rush EC, Plank LD, et al. Metformin in gestational diabetes: the offspring follow-up (MiG TOFU): body composition and metabolic outcomes at 7\u20139 years of age BMJ Open Diabetes Research and Care 2018;6:e000456. doi: 10.1136/bmjdrc-2017-00045. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29682291/","HAPO Study Cooperative Research Group, Metzger BE, Lowe LP, Dyer AR, Trimble ER, Chaovarindr U, et al. Hyperglycemia and adverse pregnancy outcomes. N Engl J Med, 2008;358:1991-2002. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMoa0707943","Toft JH, \u00d8kland I. Metformin use in pregnancy: What about long\u2010term effects in offspring? Acta Obstetricia Et Gynecologica Scandinavica. 2024 May 16;103(7):1238\u201341. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38757307/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93445"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11366"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93445"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-12T13:11:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-12T13:12:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4011"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111317"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"Gener